description: There were a few of these guys flying around and they were a good challenge to photograph. This thing was different from the pipevine and the Eastern Tiger Swallowtails. It took me a few attempts but finally this guy decided to land and I was able to get a few photos of him. He was laying in the grass where there were no flowers to feed on. His wings were spread out which is the way I like my butterfly photos. The back wing is so much more important than the underside but both can be good for ID marks but to get the good stuff it is the upper part of the wing that is the good stuff. This one was mainly black with a series of yellow dots going in a series of two rows on the back of the wing. This guy was already showing some signs of some wear and tear but still very impressive to see. This is my third swallowtail species that I have photographed. This one is a really nice one. However the Eastern Tiger so far has been chalked up on my favorites bar but this one is nothing to sneeze at it is beautiful too. It is very pretty to look at.

description: Even though their habitats differ, Desert Black Swallowtails are very similar to Anise Swallowtails (Papilio  zelicaon). They differ in the shape of the yellow marginal spots of the forewing; roundish in the Desert Black and flat in the Anise Swallowtail. At least two, possibly three, of these butterflies were seen while hiking the Tuetonia Peak Trail and try as I might, I could never catch one at rest so I have to settle with these rapid-flutter , in-flight shots. The shape of the marginal forewing spots is clearly visible though, confirming this ID.
